<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101053080899119></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101053080899119><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=101053080899119>RE: Damage Bonus ?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=101053080899119#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=35651><span id=Guru>Keyeluke</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>589 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Jan 8th 6:00 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Melee classes get a 'damage bonus' starting at level 28.&nbsp;&nbsp;This bonus is additional damage added to the base damage you do when you successfully hit a mob.  If you are dual wielding, the damage bonus applies only to your primary hand or primary hand weapon.<br><br>For one handed weapons, the damage bonus = (level-25)/3, rounded down.  So clearly, below level 28, it is zero.<br><br>For two handed weapons, the damage bonus is dependent on the delay of the weapon, with slower weapons getting bigger bonuses.  There are formulas for the damage bonus based on delay posted at monkly-business, but these formulas are no longer valid for two-handers when you are above level 51.  A recent patch increased the bonus on 2 handers at high levels, to make them more desirable.<br><br>So what does this mean to the average monk?  Since the damage bonus is applied every time you successfully hit, you want to hit more often.  This makes faster weapons more desirable, and a weapon with a 20 delay but a ratio of only 8.5 will at some point (when you're high enough level for the damage bonus to be significantly large) become better, damage-output-wise, than a weapon with a 25 delay but a ratio of 9.2.  Some of you might realize I'm comparing a Fighting Baton (8/20, ratio 8.5) and a Cane of the Tranquil (11/25, ratio 9.2).  The 'crossover point' where the weaker but faster weapon prevails varies based on the combo.  In this case, it's at level 40.  I won't go into the math of this, because I don't want to write a book here :)<br><br>Practically speaking, for dual wielders who don't want to crunch a lot of math, just put your best weapon, ratio-wise in your primary hand till about level 40, then put your fastest weapon in your primary hand.<br>&nbsp;<br>Keyeluke - <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415</a><br>Dripsy - <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=227922" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=227922</a></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
